      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1113">
               <p>James was the son of Rev. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1114.xml"
                     />John</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1112.xml"/>Elizabeth
                     (Ayscough) Hutton</persName>, who boarded scholars at Westminster School, and
                  lived in a house adjoining that of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2189.xml"
                     />Samuel Wesley Jr</persName>. in <placeName>Dean&apos;s Yard,
                     Westminster</placeName>. Like <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"
                     />CW</persName>, James Hutton was educated at Westminster. <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> became friendly with the
                  Huttons through his brothers. James was converted by <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s sermon &apos;One Thing
                  is Needful&apos;, preached on the eve of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s departure for
                     <placeName>Georgia</placeName> in <date when="1735">1735</date>. Hutton saw the
                  party off at <placeName>Gravesend</placeName>, but was dissuaded by his parents
                  from accompanying them. He followed their progress with keen interest, and the
                  Hutton home became a clearing-house for letters to and from
                     <placeName>Georgia</placeName>. On the Wesley brothers&apos; return to
                     <placeName>England</placeName>, Hutton co-operated in their religious
                  activities, and published many of their early works. When <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> split with the Moravians,
                  however, Hutton parted company with them and became a key English leader of that
                  movement. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 588–89; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 172.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
